	<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div class="gmail_quote">
<div>See the full interview by clicking on the title above.  Here is an excerpt.</div>
<div> </div>
<span style="font-family: Trebuchet MS; font-size: 14px; line-height: 22px;" /><div>
<p />
<div class="h5">
<blockquote style="color: rgb(102, 102, 102); border-color: initial; line-height: 1.222em; margin-top: 5px; margin-right: 0px; margin-bottom: 5px; margin-left: 15px; font-size: 1.4em; text-align: center; border-top-color: rgb(170, 170, 170); border-right-color: rgb(170, 170, 170); border-bottom-color: rgb(170, 170, 170); border-left-color: rgb(170, 170, 170); border-top-width: 3px !important; border-right-width: 0px !important; border-bottom-width: 3px !important; border-left-width: 0px !important; padding-top: 0px !important; padding-right: 0px !important; padding-bottom: 0px !important; padding-left: 0px !important; float: right;"><blockquote>It's easy to Twitter-face with Ruby!<br />
</blockquote></blockquote>
<blockquote>
<strong style="padding-top: 0px; padding-right: 0px; padding-bottom: 0px; padding-left: 0px; margin-top: 0px; margin-right: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px; margin-left: 0px;"><span style="font-weight: normal;">Satish&gt;&gt;</span></strong> You would be conducting a short course at RubyLearning.org on Using Twitter with Ruby. What are your thoughts on this and why did you think that such a course would be beneficial to the Ruby community.<br />
</blockquote>
<blockquote>
<strong style="padding-top: 0px; padding-right: 0px; padding-bottom: 0px; padding-left: 0px; margin-top: 0px; margin-right: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px; margin-left: 0px;"><span style="font-weight: normal;">Michael&gt;&gt;</span></strong> I'd been using Twitter for a while (my username is <a href="http://twitter.com/UziMonkey" target="_blank" style="padding-top: 0px; padding-right: 0px; padding-bottom: 0px; padding-left: 0px; margin-top: 0px; margin-right: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px; margin-left: 0px;"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); text-decoration: none;">UziMonkey</span></a>) and was vaguely aware the API was open for anyone to use, but it wasn't until I had an idea for something that I decided to check it out. I expected something complex, but what I got was something extremely simple and elegant. I immediately realized that Twitter is a natural fit to Ruby.<br />
</blockquote>
<blockquote class="posterous_medium_quote">I was up and running in no time, I hadn't realized that it would have been so easy to put my script together. Being someone always eager to share what I know, I thought this would be a useful skill for all Ruby programmers.<br />
</blockquote>
</div>
</div>
<p style="padding-top: 0px; padding-right: 0px; padding-bottom: 0px; padding-left: 0px; margin-top: 0px; margin-right: 0px; margin-left: 0px;">You can see the full interview <a href="http://rubylearning.com/blog/2009/03/17/interview-michael-morin-creator-of-using-twitter-with-ruby-course/" target="_blank">here.</a> </p> </div><div class="blogger-post-footer"><img class="posterous_download_image" src="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/2949792777916502048-199634423663007212?l=vgoff.blogspot.com" height="1" alt="" width="1" /></div>]]></content:encoded>
